Caravel Openframe for IHP SG13CMOS5L
---------------------------------------------------------

The Caravel Openframe is a concept derived from the Efabless
Caravel for the sky130 and gf180MCU open PDKs.  The idea is
that many circuit designers want to spend time designing,
simulating, testing, validating, and measuring a single
circuit or subsystem for a specific purpose.  Manufacturing
and testing that circuit requires an entire additional layer
of skills, work, and time.  The circuit under test needs
significant infrastructure:  Control logic, padframe,
stable voltage and current biases, and an interface to get
signals and data off chip to a host computer and
instrumentation.

The purpose of "openframe" is to provide that infrastructure.

This specific project is a three-level hierarchy:

(1) The "Caravel openframe" is a padframe that is pin-compatible
    with the original Efabless Caravel chip.  The size of the
    chip is variable and does not match the original Caravel
    footprint.

(2) The "openframe user project" may fill the entire area inside
    the padframe, connecting to power and ground, and analog or
    general-purpose digital I/O.

    This repository has an example openframe user project that
    is itself a multi-project carrier (or "harness") for analog
    and mixed-signal projects.  The openframe project area
    consists of a digital controller at the bottom, core
    infrastructure up the middle distributing resources to
    sixteen projects, eight on the left and eight on the right.

(3) The "pallet" is an analog user project that fits in one of the
    sixteen slots in the openframe project area.

This repository can be used as a starting point for any openframe
user project, or the existing user project can be used as-is for
new analog and mixed-signal projects.

The design flow is described here, with information about how to
create an analog project that fits into a pallet slot, or to
create an entirely new openframe project.  All design steps are
handled by scripts.

The openframe repository itself is designed to be as independent
of a specific PDK as possible, so it is relatively easy to port
between processes.  Each process will of course have its own
I/O library with its own pad definitions, which is mainly what
drives the process-specific implementation.  While porting is
made convenient, it is not really possible/practical to create
one repository that is compatible with multiple processes.  So
it is expected that an openframe repository is process-specific;
this one is for IHP SG13CMOS5L.

Unlike the original Efabless implementation, this openframe
harness design aims to have user-defined pad types in each
signal pad position (power and ground positions are still fixed,
as are a global reset input and an "option" input).
Each foundry PDK has different analog and digital cells in the
I/O library with different inputs and outputs.  The original
openframe harness was for sky130, which had an unusually
complex general-purpose I/O design that was both analog and
digital capable.  That made it convenient to design a single
fixed padframe supporting both analog and digital projects.
Since other PDKs don't have the combination I/O, it was
necessary to work out a method by which each signal pad can
be selected.  But that implies that the core-facing signals
change when any pad changes, so a large number of verilog,
schematic, and layout files have to change accordingly, which
in turn requires a large amount of automation.  This
repository provides that automation.

These instructions are currently very incomplete.  The steps
below require running individual scripts.  The scripts will
eventually be collected into a Makefile, where each step is
a process of "make <something>", and instructions will be
modified accordingly.

To create a new openframe chip with a custom user project:

(1)  Clone or fork this repository.  You probably want to create a new
     branch for the project;  then each project has the same upstream
     openframe repository but exists in its own development branch.

(2)  All scripts make use of an environment variable PDK_ROOT which
     should be set appropriately to point to the directory containing
     the PDK (ihp-sg13cmos5l).

(3)  Run the script scripts/setup.sh to import IHP open PDK library views
     into local .mag files.  This is largely specific to the IHP PDK,
     which does not have .mag views for its standard cell and I/O
     libraries.  It creates two directories, magic/sg13cmos5l_stdcell and
     magic/sg13cmos5l_io, and populates them with .mag files, so that
     working in magic does not require reading the GDS of the PDK
     libraries each time.

(4)  Edit the "config.txt" file.  This contains a "project_id" value which
     is an arbitrary hex string of 8 digits.  This corresponds to a metal
     text block on the layout, and a digital 32-bit ID value made available
     to the openframe project.  It is recommended that the last four bits
     of the code be reserved for a revision number.

     This is followed by a list of signal pads.  The signal pads are
     listed in counter-clockwise order of their physical position in the
     padframe.  This allows the openframe project designer to choose
     whether each of the 44 signal pads will be analog, or digital
     input, output, or bidirectional.  The user does not need to supply
     any additional information about the pads.  The top level pin names
     will remain the same ("gpio[*]"), and the internal signal names will
     be derived from the pad signal names, with an index.

     The signal pad list entries are in the form:

		gpio[x]:  pad_name

     Example:
		gpio[36]: sg13cmos5l_IOPadInOut4mA

     Core signal names are derived from a signal name.  For the
     SG13CMOS5L technology, if the pad is a digital input-only or
     digital output-only pad, then there is only one core facing signal,
     which is what is given in the config.txt file.  If the pad is an
     analog pad, there are two signals, one of which is the pad name
     (that is, the core name = the pad name because there is a direct
     connection to the pad and the signals are the same), and the other
     of which is the given signal name.  If the pad is one of the "InOut"
     pads, then there are five core signals <signal_name>_in,
     <signal_name>_out, <signal_name>_ena, <signal_name>_one, and
     <signal_name>_zero.  The first three are the pad-to-core signal, the
     core-to-pad signal, and the output enable signal, respectively.  The
     additional two signals are digital zero and one outputs provided next
     to the pad so that a project can opt to tie off control signals at the
     pad, or to use these to power digital logic close to the pad.  In the
     example above, the core facing signals would be:

		flash_io2_out
		flash_io2_in
		flash_io2_ena
		flash_io2_one
		flash_io2_zero

     Note that only the 44 GPIO pads can be reassigned.  The power pads
     and the master reset input and option input are fixed.  The option
     input exists because the original Caravel definition had 63 pins.
     If the original wire bonding is used, then the option pin is
     inaccessible and becomes a "downbond" option.  If all 64 pins are
     wired to 64 pins of a package, then it becomes an additional
     input.

     To recap:  For SG13CMOS5L's PDK I/O library, there are eleven pad
     types, with pin and core names derived per the following example:

     1. Input-only pad:

	gpio[0]:	sg13cmos5l_IOPadIn	mysig

		pad signal is:		gpio[0]
		core signal is:		mysig

     2. Output-only pad:

	gpio[0]:	sg13cmos5l_IOPadOut4mA	mysig

		pad signal is:		gpio[0]
		core signal is:		mysig

     3. Medium-drive output-only pad:

	gpio[0]:	sg13cmos5l_IOPadOut16mA	mysig

		pad signal is:		gpio[0]
		core signal is:		mysig

     4. High-drive output-only pad:

	gpio[0]:	sg13cmos5l_IOPadOut30mA	mysig

		pad signal is:		gpio[0]
		core signal is:		mysig

     5. Tri-state output-only pad:

	gpio[0]:	sg13cmos5l_IOPadTriOut4mA	mysig

		pad signal is:		gpio[0]
		core signals are:	mysig
					mysig_ena

     6. Medium-drive tri-state output-only pad:

	gpio[0]:	sg13cmos5l_IOPadTriOut16mA	mysig

		pad signal is:		gpio[0]
		core signals are:	mysig
					mysig_ena
					mysig_zero
					mysig_one

     7. High-drive tri-state output-only pad:

	gpio[0]:	sg13cmos5l_IOPadTriOut30mA	mysig

		pad signal is:		gpio[0]
		core signals are:	mysig
					mysig_ena
					mysig_zero
					mysig_one

     8. Bidrectional pad:

	gpio[0]:	sg13cmos5l_IOPadInOut4mA	mysig

		pad signal is:		gpio[0]
		core signals are:	mysig_in
					mysig_out
					mysig_ena
					mysig_zero
					mysig_one
     9. Medium-drive bidrectional pad:

	gpio[0]:	sg13cmos5l_IOPadInOut16mA	mysig

		pad signal is:		gpio[0]
		core signals are:	mysig_in
					mysig_out
					mysig_ena
					mysig_zero
					mysig_one

     10. High-drive bidrectional pad:

	gpio[0]:	sg13cmos5l_IOPadInOut30mA	mysig

		pad signal is:		gpio[0]
		core signals are:	mysig_in
					mysig_out
					mysig_ena
					mysig_zero
					mysig_one

     11. Analog pad:

	gpio[0]:	sg13cmos5l_IOPadInOut30mA	mysig

		pad signal is:		gpio[0]
		core signals are:	gpio[0]
					mysig

     Signals should not be indexed, as then different signals would
     have different index ranges which would not match the indexes of
     the pads.

     All pads in this library are the same size.

(5)  Run the script "scripts/parse_config.py".  This script reads
     in the configuration file and produces:

	1) A verilog netlist of the padframe in verilog/gl/sg13cmos5l_padframe.v
	2) A verilog netlist of the user project wrapper in
	   verilog/gl/openframe_project_wrapper.v
	3) A Tcl script used in the next step to generate the padframe
	   and wrapper layouts.

     If the script determines that any of the output files already exist,
     it will not run.  Delete the existing files before re-running the
     config file parser.

     WARNING:  Because the "openframe_project_wrapper" layout and verilog
     contain the user project, MAKE SURE that you do not overwrite
     existing layout and netlist work.  The best policy is to create a
     layout hierarchy with the user project in a cell called
     "openframe_user_project" which is simply dropped into the wrapper.
     (See comments below about creating the user project layout.)
     No verilog netlist is made for the user project itself, which is
     assumed to be analog/mixed signal and exist as a schematic, not
     verilog.

(6)  Run the script "scripts/run_gen_padframe.sh".  This script reads
     in the configuration file and produces:

	1) A padframe layout in magic/sg13cmos5l_padframe.mag
	2) The user project wrapper layout in magic/openframe_project_wrapper.mag

     This script must be run from the magic/ directory.  If the script
     determines that a file "sg13cmos5_padframe.mag" exists, it will not
     run.  It may be run again at any time by deleting the padframe layout.

(7)  Run the script "set_user_id.py".  This script reads the configuration
     file and produces:

	1) A modified layout "user_id_textblock.mag" with the text of the
	   project ID in metal
	2) A modified layout "user_id_vias.mag" with the via programming
	   for the 32-bit ROM matching the project ID.
	3) A modified "caravel_openframe.v" with the project ID set
	4) A modified "user_id_programming.v" with the project ID bits set

Now the openframe project is set up and ready for the project wrapper
area to be completed.  As mentioned above, the user project for an analog
or mixed-signa chip is generally done as a schematic.  The pinout of the
user project itself does not need to match the names in the wrapper.  The
wrapper is the place where the user project is instantiated and wired up
to the wrapper pins.

(8)  If there are digital synthesized blocks inside the user project, then
     they should be run through LibreLane individually.  From the output of
     LibreLane, copy the verilog netlist from the flow after fill insertion
     (in the "standard" flow, this is 51-openroad-fillinsertion/).  Use the
     ".pnl.v" file, which is the one that has power pins defined on the
     standard cells, and is appropriate for LVS.  You will also want the
     ".nl.v" netlist for mixed-mode simulation.  This works best if your
     verilog includes module files from a single file listing all of the
     includes.  Either keep a separate list file for each purpose (LVS
     or simulation), or use "`ifdef SIM" and/or "`ifdef LVS" in the file
     to choose the appropriate netlist.

     Copy the layout from the post-stream-out directory.  In the "standard"
     LibreLane flow, this is 55-magic-streamout-1.  The layout should be
     the ".mag" file, not the GDS, as the ".mag" file keeps references to
     the standard cell, not complete copies of the standard cells.

(9)  The user project top level works best as a separate level of hierarchy
     from the wrapper.  By convention, this is called "openframe_user_project"
     although it can be called anything.  These instructions will refer to
     the user project cell as "openframe_user_project".

     The tools that prepare the openframe will regenerate the wrapper files.
     Keeping the user project in a separate hierarchical level avoids the
     misfortune of accidentally deleting the entire user project.  In the
     worst case, the user project layout needs only to be placed inside the
     wrapper layout, and the user project module needs to be placed in the
     wrapper module with appropriate signal connections.  With the separated
     hierarchy, the file "openframe_project_wrapper.v" instances the module
     "openframe_user_project" (see above), which typically will not exist
     as a verilog module at all, but as a schematic.

(10) These instructions are not meant to cover how to create the user project
     other than mentioning how to pull results from LibreLane (see above)
     and how to connect the project to the wrapper.  As a general
     recommendation, however, the layout is best done by first dumping the
     openframe_project_wrapper layout contents into the openframe_user_project
     layout.  Pin labels can then be erased where they are not used, or
     renamed to match the user project pinout.  This will ensure that when
     the user project is later placed inside the wrapper, the pins will match
     exactly.  Do not edit the wrapper itself other than to place the user
     project inside it, as the pins and boundary are placed to exactly match
     to the padframe.

Once the user project itself is created and validated, the assembly into
the final chip goes as follows:

(11) Run the script "run_gen_wrapper_gds.sh".
     The script "run_gen_wrapper_gds.sh" creates GDS of the user project
     wrapper and its contents.  Note that as a custom analog layout,
     magic should generate GDS with hierarchical corrections, which is
     the default way that magic writes GDS.  Top level assembly is
     different;  because everything outside of the wrapper is a PDK
     library component (I/O cell or standard cell), no hierarchical
     processing is needed, which greatly increases the speed at which
     magic writes the GDS output.  "run_gen_wrapper_gds.sh" creates
     the GDS file which is then pulled into the final chip verbatim.
     The GDS file is "gds/openframe_project_wrapper.gds.gz".

(12) Run the script "run_gen_openframe_gds.sh".  This step assembles
     the user project wrapper GDS created in the previous step with
     the padframe and seal ring, generates a (pre-fill) top-level
     .mag file of the layout, and writes out a (pre-fill) top-level
     GDS file called "gds/sg13cmos5l_caravel_openframe.gds.gz".

(13) "cd" to the gds/ directory and run the script "generate_fill.py"
     as follows:

	../scripts/generate_fill.py sg13cmos5l_caravel_openframe.gds.gz -dist 

     This step generates the fill patterns for the chip, in a separate
     GDS file called sg13cmos5l_caravel_openframe_fill_pattern.gds.gz.

(14) Run the script "run_gen_filled_final_gds.sh" to get the (post-fill)
     final design.  The final top level has its own cell name.  By default
     (which is not an IHP-approved name) the top level cell will be
     called "sg13cmos5l_caravel_openframe_final".  For IHP submissions, IHP
     will provide the name of the top level cell as part of the submission
     process.  To get the correct final top level cell name and file name,
     set the environment variable "PROJECT" to the cell name before running
     the script.

(15) Final DRC verification:  The script "run_klayout_drc_final.sh" runs
     klayout DRC on the final design GDS.  If environment PROJECT has been
     set (see above), then the final DRC result can be found in
     validate/${PROJECT}.lyrdb

(16) Final LVS verification:  The script "run_extract_openframe.sh" does a
     full layout extraction on the top level, producing a netlist that
     is placed in netlist/layout/.  If the PROJECT environment variable
     has been set, then the final netlist is netlist/layout/${PROJECT}.spice.

(17) Final LVS:  The script "run_lvs_openframe.sh" runs top-level LVS.
     Note that since the LVS process is highly dependent on what exists
     in the user project area, this script needs to be modified for each
     project.  It is normally set up to start with the top level verilog
     and read the user project from a netlist, which should be extracted
     from the user project schematic.  Everything above the user project
     is in a verilog netlist.  If the top level cell has been named
     according to environment variable PROJECT, then a top level verilog
     netlist needs to be made for a module with the name ${PROJECT}.  This
     is easy to do by copying the "sg13cmos5l_caravel_openframe_final.v"
     file to ${PROJECT}.v and changing the module name to ${PROJECT}.

     [To do:  Currently top level LVS through magic and netgen fails due
     to issues in the padframe I/O netlists in the PDK, which need to be
     resolved.  Checking LVS with klayout has not been attempted and would
     require converting the verilog of the padframe, wrapper, and top
     level cell to SPICE/CDL]
     
-------------------------------------------------------------------
Mixed-signal multi-project mixed-signal harness
-------------------------------------------------------------------

This repository contains a full example of an openframe design in
the form of a multi-project mixed-signal harness design.  This
is a framework for aggregating up to sixteen analog or mixed-signal
sub-projects, each one able to be separately powered.

The user project has dependent libraries which are hierarchical
and therefore also independent git projects.  They should be
instantiated as git submodules.  The submodules can be cloned with
the project by doing

git clone https://github.com/RTimothyEdwards/sg13cmos5l_ocd_ip__openframe.git \
	--recurse-submodules

or after cloning, by doing

git submodule update --init --recursive

That initializes the dependent repositories used for the project
example.  For a different project, new submodules can be added by
first creating the IP as a git project, use

git submodule add <repository_URL>

For simplicity, keep the subdirectory name the same as the repository.
After adding the submodule, commit and push as usual.

-------------------------------------------------------------------
Mixed-signal sub-projects
-------------------------------------------------------------------

The mixed-signal aggregator has not yet formalized the areas available
for analog and mixed-signal projects.  The idea is that the empty area
of the chip is divided into sixteen slots (or "pallets").  Each pallet
has an identical footprint.  It gets its 3.3V power supply from a
pMOS power switch, and is given pins to connect to the digital interface
of the harness (control and status lines), regulated voltage bias
signals, and regulated current bias signals (either source or sink,
although the sinks are not regulated).  More information will be
provided on the creation of analog and mixed-signal projects when
the project resources and footprint are defined.
